equation_narrative.headline: Positive charge requirement recognized early, K selected over R via local sequence context
equation_narrative.story: Position 6 in ubiquitin sits in a charged, surface-exposed environment with 8 structural contacts and 4 co-evolving positions. The model assembles a representation consistent with positively charged residues by layer 8 (K at 32%, R at 7%), though the logit lens shows volatile early fluctuations through polar candidates (N peaks at 28% L6, Q at 18% L7) as the model integrates structural and evolutionary signals. The decision phase begins at L24 with strong K-specific prediction channels activating. By L30, MLP neuron N30:620 delivers a decisive 1.58 projection toward K, and the final layers consolidate this choice to 98.87% confidence, correctly distinguishing K from the chemically similar R based on local sequence preferences.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 assemble a representation of a positively charged, surface-exposed position through multiple information streams. Eight structural contacts are read, though attention head L29:18 later acts as a structural eraser (-4.62 projection). Four co-evolving positions provide evolutionary constraints favoring charged residues. Early features (F1:9146, F1:5480, F1:1508 all ~45 proj) encode the local sequence context around MQIFV_TLTGK. The logit lens shows volatile character shifts—S leads initially (22.6% L1), then H (28.7% L4), then N (27.7% L6-7), reflecting the model's integration of polar and charged signals. By L8, K emerges (31.6%) as the representation stabilizes toward positive charge, though hydrophobic candidates (A, V) briefly dominate L12-13 as the model processes burial/exposure features. The representation settles at L23 with K at 32.6% and R at 11.5%, indicating a positively charged character has been established.
perception_phase.context_character: Surface-exposed position requiring positive charge, with local sequence context MQIFV_TLTGK providing specificity. The representation by L23 is strongly charged-positive, distinguishing this from hydrophobic core positions despite brief hydrophobic signals during mid-layer processing.
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: 8 residues, though L29:18 attention head later erases structural signal (-4.62 proj, 0.882 structural attention)
Co-evolutionary coupling: 4 positions providing evolutionary constraint toward charged residues
Local sequence features: F1:9146, F1:5480, F1:1508 (all ~45 proj) encode MQIFV_TLTGK context
L9 attention features: F9:5728 (48.97 proj), F9:1281 (44.96 proj) integrate structural and sequence information
L18 features: F18:7701 (13.14 proj) marks transition toward decision-relevant representations

decision_phase.summary: The decision phase begins at L24 with K-specific prediction channels activating (F24:2313 at 16.83 proj, F24:5827 at 16.43 proj). Layer 30 delivers the decisive push: MLP neuron N30:620 projects 1.583 toward K, while attention features F30:2305 (46.67 proj) and F30:9379 (33.16 proj) consolidate the choice. K rises from 32.6% at L23 to 58.9% at L29 to 98.87% at L33. The final layers (L31-33) suppress R (from 9.6% to 0.95%) through strong K-specific features F33:4166 (122.74 proj) and F33:6423 (119.61 proj), while MLP layer L32 shows net negative activity (-5.47 total) that refines the K vs R distinction.
decision_phase.transition: At L23-25, the representation shifts from encoding 'positively charged context' to activating K-specific prediction channels. L24 features F24:2313 and F24:5827 are the first high-projection attention features with strong K-specificity, marking where the model commits to K over the chemically similar R. The logit lens shows K holding steady (32.6% L23 → 30.5% L24) while decision machinery engages.

candidates.narrative: K dominates the decision phase through coordinated MLP and attention support. At L30, neuron N30:620 delivers a massive 1.583 projection (top vote among all neurons), while attention features F30:2305 (46.67 proj) and F30:9379 (33.16 proj) consolidate the choice. The final layers activate ultra-high-projection K-specific channels: F33:4166 (122.74 proj), F33:6423 (119.61 proj), and MLP features F33:3601 (119.54 proj) and F33:9445 (116.76 proj). K rises from 58.9% at L29 to 98.87% at L33, suppressing all alternatives including the chemically similar R.
candidates.key_layers: Emerges L7-8 (31.6%), consolidates L29-30 (58.9%), dominates L33 (98.87%)
key_evidence: N30:620 (MLP, 1.583 proj) — strongest single neuron vote for K
F30:2305 (attn, 46.67 proj) — high-confidence K prediction channel

candidates.narrative: R is the chemically similar alternative (both positively charged), peaking early at 14.3% (L10) when the representation encodes general positive charge character. R maintains 11.5% at L23 as the perception phase concludes, but loses decisively in the decision phase as K-specific features activate. By L29, R drops to 9.6%, and final-layer suppression reduces it to 0.95%. The model distinguishes K from R based on local sequence context rather than charge alone, as evidenced by the lack of R-specific high-projection features in L24-33.
key_evidence: No high-projection R-specific features in decision layers L24-33
Suppressed by K-specific channels F33:4166, F33:6423 in final layers

candidates.narrative: N dominates the logit lens at L6-7 (27.7% peak), reflecting the model's integration of polar signals during perception. This is NOT a prediction—the representation at L6 happens to project toward polar residues as the model reads structural contacts and local sequence. N's early prominence reflects the polar character of intermediate representations, not a belief about the answer. N fades rapidly after L23 (3.0%) as K-specific decision features activate, finishing at 0.1%.
candidates.key_layers: Logit lens peaks L6-7 (27.7%), collapses L23+ (3.0% → 0.1%)
key_evidence: Early logit lens artifact during polar signal integration (L6-7)
No N-specific features in decision phase L24-33
Representation character shifts from polar to charged-positive by L8

candidates.narrative: Q peaks at L7 (17.7%) during the perception phase as the model integrates polar and charged signals. Like N, this reflects the representation's polar-leaning character at that layer, not a model prediction. Q briefly leads the logit lens at L7 before K takes over. Q maintains low presence through L23 (1.5%) and is fully suppressed in the decision phase (0.03% final), lacking any high-projection features in L24-33.
candidates.key_layers: Logit lens peaks L7 (17.7%), suppressed L24+ (1.5% → 0.03%)
key_evidence: Logit lens lead at L7 during polar signal integration
No Q-specific decision features in L24-33
Fully suppressed by K-specific channels in final layers

candidates.narrative: V briefly leads the logit lens at L13 (16.4%) and L18 (16.2%), reflecting a transient hydrophobic character in the representation as the model processes burial/exposure features. This is a mid-layer artifact—the representation temporarily correlates with hydrophobic residues while integrating structural information, but this does not reflect a model belief. V is suppressed in the decision phase, finishing at negligible probability.
candidates.key_layers: Logit lens peaks L13, L18 (~16%), suppressed L24+
key_evidence: Mid-layer logit lens artifact during burial/exposure processing
No V-specific features in decision phase
Hydrophobic signal overridden by charged-positive context by L23

turning_points.description: The representation shifts from polar-leaning (N at 27.7% L6, Q at 17.7% L7) to charged-positive (K at 31.6% L8). This reflects the model's integration of evolutionary and structural signals that establish the positive charge requirement. Features F9:5728 (48.97 proj) and F9:1281 (44.96 proj) encode this consolidated charged-positive character. This is a perception-phase shift in representation character, not a decision.

A brief hydrophobic excursion occurs as the logit lens shows A (14.2% L12) and V (16.4% L13) leading, likely reflecting the model's processing of burial/exposure features. MLP L12 shows mixed activity (N12:3486 writes 0.63 toward K, but N12:2942 erases -0.33). By L14, K reasserts dominance (23.5%) as the charged-positive representation stabilizes. This volatility is characteristic of mid-layer feature integration, not decision uncertainty.

The decisive commitment occurs here. L29 MLP neurons deliver strong K support: N29:3758 (0.628 proj), N29:643 (0.565 proj), N29:4362 (0.550 proj). L30 MLP neuron N30:620 provides the single strongest vote (1.583 proj), while attention features F30:2305 (46.67 proj) and F30:9379 (33.16 proj) consolidate. K rises from 32.6% (L23) to 58.9% (L29) to 95.0% (L30). This is where the model commits to K over R based on local sequence specificity.

deep_dives.label: Early sequence encoding (L1, L9)
deep_dives.caption: L1 features (F1:9146, F1:5480, F1:1508 all ~45 proj) encode the local sequence context MQIFV_TLTGK. L9 features (F9:5728 at 48.97 proj, F9:1281 at 44.96 proj) show the consolidated charged-positive representation after structural and evolutionary signals are integrated.

deep_dives.label: Mid-layer representation shifts (L12-14 MLP)
deep_dives.caption: L12-14 MLPs show the model processing burial/exposure features, causing brief hydrophobic signals (A, V in logit lens). N12:3486 writes strongly toward K (0.632), but N12:2942 erases (-0.329). By L14, K-specific neurons (N14:1012 at 0.287, N14:2776 at 0.261) stabilize the charged-positive representation.

deep_dives.label: Structural signal erasure (L29 attention)
deep_dives.caption: L29 head 18 is a major structural eraser (-4.62 projection, 0.882 structural attention), removing structural contact information that might favor alternative residues. This clears the way for sequence-based K-specificity to dominate.

deep_dives.label: Decision onset (L24 SAE features)
deep_dives.caption: L24 marks the transition to decision mode. F24:2313 (16.83 proj) and F24:5827 (16.43 proj) are the first high-projection K-specific prediction channels, indicating the model has committed to K over R. These features have strong K-specificity unlike earlier general charged-positive features.

deep_dives.label: Decisive MLP push (L29-30)
deep_dives.caption: L29-30 MLPs deliver the decisive K commitment. N29:3758 (0.628), N29:643 (0.565), and N29:4362 (0.550) provide strong L29 support. N30:620 delivers the single strongest neuron vote (1.583 proj toward K), driving K from 58.9% to 95.0%. This is where local sequence context definitively selects K over R.

deep_dives.label: Final K consolidation (L33 features)
deep_dives.caption: L33 features provide ultra-high-projection K-specific support: F33:4166 (122.74 proj), F33:6423 (119.61 proj), F33:3601 (119.54 proj), F33:9445 (116.76 proj). These final-layer channels suppress all alternatives, bringing K to 98.87% confidence and reducing R to 0.95%.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly predicts K by assembling a charged-positive surface-exposed context through L1-23, then distinguishing K from the chemically similar R via local sequence specificity in L24-33. The decisive evidence comes at L30, where MLP neuron N30:620 delivers a 1.583 projection toward K—the strongest single neuron vote in the entire forward pass—based on the MQIFV_TLTGK sequence context. Final-layer features F33:4166 (122.74 proj) and F33:6423 (119.61 proj) consolidate this choice to 98.87% confidence, demonstrating that ESM-2 distinguishes between chemically similar charged residues through fine-grained sequence preferences rather than charge alone.
